4:15:38 PM [express] GET /api/guidelines/type/ICD-10-CM 200 in 3ms :: {"data":[{"id":"1-C1.a","chapter":1,"chapterTitle":"Certain Infectious and Parasitic Diseases","section":"C1.a","title":"Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) Infections — Code Selection","content":"Code only confirmed cases of HIV infection/illness. In this context, 'confirmation' does not require documentation of positive serology or culture for HIV; the provider's diagnostic statement that the patient is HIV positive, or has an HIV-related illness is sufficient. Select code B20, Human immunodeficiency virus [HIV] disease, when the patient has a confirmed HIV diagnosis AND is admitted for an HIV-related condition or is described as having a condition(s) resulting from HIV. In that instance the HIV disease code, B20, is sequenced first, followed by additional diagnosis codes for all reported HIV-related conditions.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"B99","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["HIV","infectious disease","B20","sequencing","confirmation"]},{"id":"1-C1.b","chapter":1,"chapterTitle":"Certain Infectious and Parasitic Diseases","section":"C1.b","title":"HIV — Asymptomatic HIV Infection","content":"Code Z21, Asymptomatic human immunodeficiency virus [HIV] infection status, is to be applied when the patient without any documentation of symptoms is listed as being 'HIV positive,' 'known HIV,' 'HIV test positive,' or similar terminology. Code Z21 may also be used when the patient has an HIV infection but has not been treated for nor developed any HIV-related conditions. Do not use this code if the term 'AIDS' or 'HIV disease' is used, in which case code B20 should be assigned.","codeRangeStart":"A00","codeRangeEnd":"B99","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["HIV","asymptomatic","Z21","B20","AIDS"]},{"id":"1-C1.d","chapter":1,"chapterTitle":"Certain Infectious and Parasitic Diseases","section":"C1.d","title":"Sepsis, Severe Sepsis, and Septic Shock","content":"For a diagnosis of sepsis, assign the appropriate code for the underlying systemic infection. If the type of infection or causal organism is not further specified, assign code A41.9, Sepsis, unspecified organism. A code from subcategory R65.2, Severe sepsis, should also be assigned as an additional code if the medical record documentation includes that the patient has severe sepsis (i.e., sepsis with organ dysfunction). If a patient has sepsis and an associated acute organ dysfunction or multiple organ dysfunction (MOD), follow the instructions for coding severe sepsis.","codeRangeStart":"A40","codeRangeEnd":"A41","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["sepsis","A41.9","R65.2","severe sepsis","septic shock","organ dysfunction"]},{"id":"1-C1.d.1","chapter":1,"chapterTitle":"Certain Infectious and Parasitic Diseases","section":"C1.d.1","title":"Septic Shock","content":"Septic shock generally refers to circulatory failure associated with severe sepsis, and therefore, represents a type of acute organ dysfunction. For all cases of septic shock, the code for the systemic infection should be sequenced first, followed by code R65.21, Severe sepsis with septic shock or code T81.12, Postprocedural septic shock. Any additional codes for the other acute organ dysfunctions should also be assigned. As noted in the sequencing instructions in the Tabular List, the code for septic shock cannot be assigned as a principal diagnosis.","codeRangeStart":"A40","codeRangeEnd":"A41","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["septic shock","R65.21","T81.12","sequencing","principal diagnosis"]},{"id":"1-C1.h","chapter":1,"chapterTitle":"Certain Infectious and Parasitic Diseases","section":"C1.h","title":"COVID-19 Infections","content":"Code U07.1, COVID-19, should be assigned for a confirmed (positive lab test) or presumptive COVID-19 diagnosis. For purposes of CMS coding, a confirmed diagnosis does not require a positive lab result; the provider's documentation of the diagnosis is sufficient. When the reason for the encounter/admission is for COVID-19, assign code U07.1 as the principal/first-listed diagnosis. For MIS-C or MIS-A associated with COVID-19, assign codes M35.81 or M35.89 plus U07.1.","codeRangeStart":"U07","codeRangeEnd":"U07","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["COVID-19","U07.1","coronavirus","confirmed diagnosis","MIS-C","pandemic"]},{"id":"2-C2.a","chapter":2,"chapterTitle":"Neoplasms","section":"C2.a","title":"Treatment Directed at Primary Site vs Metastatic Site","content":"When treatment is directed at the malignancy, designate the malignancy as the principal diagnosis. The only exception to this guideline is if a patient admission/encounter is solely for the administration of chemotherapy, immunotherapy or external beam radiation therapy, assign the appropriate Z51 code as the first-listed or principal diagnosis, and the diagnosis or problem for which the service is being performed as a secondary diagnosis.","codeRangeStart":"C00","codeRangeEnd":"D49","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["neoplasm","cancer","malignancy","primary site","chemotherapy","Z51"]},{"id":"2-C2.b","chapter":2,"chapterTitle":"Neoplasms","section":"C2.b","title":"Neoplasm — Primary Malignancy Previously Excised","content":"When a primary malignancy has been previously excised or eradicated from its site and there is no further treatment directed to that site and there is no evidence of any existing primary malignancy at that site, a code from category Z85, Personal history of malignant neoplasm, should be used to indicate the former site of the malignancy. Any mention of extension, invasion, or metastasis to another site is coded as a secondary malignant neoplasm to that site.","codeRangeStart":"C00","codeRangeEnd":"D49","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["neoplasm","Z85","history","excised","metastasis","secondary"]},{"id":"2-C2.m","chapter":2,"chapterTitle":"Neoplasms","section":"C2.m","title":"Malignant Neoplasm in a Pregnant Patient","content":"When a pregnant woman has a malignant neoplasm, a code from subcategory O9A.1-, Malignant neoplasm complicating pregnancy, childbirth, and the puerperium, should be sequenced first, followed by the appropriate code from Chapter 2 to indicate the type of neoplasm. Any mention of a complication associated with the malignancy should also be reported.","codeRangeStart":"C00","codeRangeEnd":"D49","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["neoplasm","pregnancy","O9A.1","malignant","complication"]},{"id":"4-C4.a","chapter":4,"chapterTitle":"Endocrine, Nutritional and Metabolic Diseases","section":"C4.a","title":"Diabetes Mellitus — Code Assignment","content":"The diabetes mellitus codes are combination codes that include the type of diabetes mellitus, the body system affected, and the complications affecting that body system. As many codes within a particular category as necessary should be used to describe all of the complications of the disease. They should be sequenced based on the reason for a particular encounter. Assign as many codes from categories E08-E13 as needed to identify all of the associated conditions that the patient has.","codeRangeStart":"E00","codeRangeEnd":"E89","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["diabetes","E08","E09","E10","E11","E13","combination codes","complications"]},{"id":"4-C4.a.1","chapter":4,"chapterTitle":"Endocrine, Nutritional and Metabolic Diseases","section":"C4.a.1","title":"Type 1 vs Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus","content":"Type 1 diabetes mellitus is coded to category E10, Type 1 diabetes mellitus. Type 2 diabetes mellitus is coded to category E11, Type 2 diabetes mellitus. If the documentation does not specify the type, default to type 2. Age alone is not a determining factor. If a type 2 patient uses insulin, assign an additional code from category Z79.4, Long-term (current) use of insulin, or Z79.84, Long-term (current) use of oral hypoglycemic drugs. Do not assign Z79.4 if insulin is given as a temporary measure.","codeRangeStart":"E10","codeRangeEnd":"E11","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["diabetes","type 1","type 2","E10","E11","Z79.4","insulin","unspecified"]},{"id":"4-C4.a.3","chapter":4,"chapterTitle":"Endocrine, Nutritional and Metabolic Diseases","section":"C4.a.3","title":"Secondary Diabetes Mellitus","content":"Codes under categories E08, Diabetes mellitus due to underlying condition, E09, Drug or chemical induced diabetes mellitus, and E13, Other specified diabetes mellitus, identify complications/manifestations associated with secondary diabetes mellitus. Secondary diabetes is always caused by another condition or event. The sequencing of the secondary diabetes codes is based on the reason for a particular encounter. Assign as many codes from categories E08, E09, and E13 as needed.","codeRangeStart":"E08","codeRangeEnd":"E13","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["diabetes","secondary diabetes","E08","E09","E13","drug-induced","sequencing"]},{"id":"9-C9.a","chapter":9,"chapterTitle":"Diseases of the Circulatory System","section":"C9.a","title":"Hypertension — Coding Rules","content":"A causal relationship is presumed between hypertension and heart involvement and between hypertension and chronic kidney disease (CKD), whether or not the provider has documented a link between these conditions. Unless the provider specifically documents that hypertension is not related to the CKD or the heart disease, code both together. Assign codes from categories I10-I16 (hypertension), with a code from I50 (heart failure) if applicable, and with a code from N18 (CKD) if applicable.","codeRangeStart":"I00","codeRangeEnd":"I99","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["hypertension","I10","CKD","heart failure","I50","N18","causal relationship"]},{"id":"9-C9.b","chapter":9,"chapterTitle":"Diseases of the Circulatory System","section":"C9.b","title":"Coronary Artery Disease — CABG and Stent Coding","content":"ICD-10-CM has combination codes for atherosclerotic heart disease with angina pectoris. These combination codes include stenosis of native coronary arteries or bypass grafts. When using one of these combination codes it is not necessary to use an additional code for angina pectoris. A causal relationship can be assumed in a patient with both atherosclerosis and angina pectoris, unless the documentation indicates the angina is due to something other than the atherosclerosis.","codeRangeStart":"I20","codeRangeEnd":"I25","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["coronary artery disease","CABG","stent","atherosclerosis","angina","I20","I25"]},{"id":"9-C9.d","chapter":9,"chapterTitle":"Diseases of the Circulatory System","section":"C9.d","title":"Cerebrovascular Disease — Stroke and Sequelae Coding","content":"Category I69, Sequelae of cerebrovascular disease, specifies the type of stroke that caused the sequela. The neurological deficits caused by cerebrovascular disease may be present from the onset or may arise at any time after the onset of the condition. Codes from category I69 may be assigned on a health care record with codes from I60-I67 if the patient has a current CVA and a sequela of a previous CVA. Code Z86.73, Personal history of TIA, and cerebral infarction without residual deficits, should be assigned when the patient's history indicates a previous CVA.","codeRangeStart":"I60","codeRangeEnd":"I69","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["stroke","CVA","I69","sequelae","TIA","cerebrovascular","I60","neurological deficits"]},{"id":"9-C9.f","chapter":9,"chapterTitle":"Diseases of the Circulatory System","section":"C9.f","title":"Heart Failure — Combination Coding and Sequencing","content":"Heart failure is coded with combination codes from category I50. Diastolic and systolic heart failure are classified by type and acuity. If the documentation specifies both, assign the combination code. For heart failure due to hypertension, use the I11.- (hypertensive heart disease) or I13.- (hypertensive heart and CKD disease) category codes, plus the appropriate I50 code. Code the type of heart failure if documented. If combined systolic and diastolic, assign only the combination code and not separate codes.","codeRangeStart":"I50","codeRangeEnd":"I50","type":"ICD-10-CM","sourceUrl":"https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/2026-icd-10-cm-guidelines","tags":["heart failure","I50","systolic","diastolic","I11","I13","hypertension","combination code"]}],"total":30,"page":1,"pageSize":15,"hasMore":true}
4:15:38 PM [express] GET /api/guidelines/stats 200 in 2ms :: {"totalGuidelines":46,"icdChapters":11,"cptGuidelines":3,"hcpcsGuidelines":3,"lastSync":"2026-03-11T16:15:38.107Z","chapters":[{"chapter":0,"title":"General Coding Guidelines","count":16},{"chapter":1,"title":"Certain Infectious and Parasitic Diseases","count":5},{"chapter":2,"title":"Neoplasms","count":3},{"chapter":4,"title":"Endocrine, Nutritional and Metabolic Diseases","count":3},{"chapter":5,"title":"Mental, Behavioral and Neurodevelopmental Disorders","count":1},{"chapter":9,"title":"Diseases of the Circulatory System","count":5},{"chapter":10,"title":"Diseases of the Respiratory System","count":2},{"chapter":13,"title":"Diseases of the Musculoskeletal System and Connective Tissue","count":2},{"chapter":15,"title":"Pregnancy, Childbirth and the Puerperium","count":2},{"chapter":18,"title":"Symptoms, Signs and Abnormal Clinical and Laboratory Findings","count":1},{"chapter":19,"title":"Injury, Poisoning and Certain Other Consequences of External Causes","count":3},{"chapter":21,"title":"Factors Influencing Health Status and Contact with Health Services","count":3}]}
